Customer Service: 2/5, Food: 5/5. this review is going to be long, fair warning, but worth the read.  I visited this restaurant on November 1, 2020. I had ordered from this restaurant many times during the quarantine but never went in person. I was super excited to bring my friend, who is from out of town, to this restaurant. I had raved about it all morning and was excited to do brunch. To my dismay, One of the co-owners has a very bad disposition. I was so excited to support a business that is not only black owned but also by women. when I came in I asked for a seat for two. The owner who is taller with lighter hair said to me, in an annoyed and overly assertive tone, “WE DON’T HAVE ANY TABLES FOR TWO AT THE MOMENT.” I didn’t take it personally I just assumed the restaurant was hectic. I waited for a second assuming she would tell me how long the wait was but she didn’t. I proceed to ask how long until one will be available and that is when she told me 15 minutes. We came back in exactly 17 minutes because we needed to find parking. As soon as I walked in she yells over the counter “I gave away your table because I didn’t think you were coming back. I told you to come back in 10 minutes.” I politely reminded her that she actually told me 15 minutes. She then says “you’re right well that was 20 minutes ago at this point.” I didn’t argue. I was so embarrassed that she was being so rude. I wondered if maybe I knew her from somewhere or if I had done something. It wasn’t what she said it was how she said it. She was so mean. She then offered us to sit bar side and we chose that because it was pouring outside and we were hungry. My friend asked how could I like a restaurant like this if the staff was so rude and I told her that I had never actually been there but I only ordered through seamless. She spoke with everyone she interacted with like that, it wasn’t just me. Her tone is comparable to a snarky and entitled teenager. I left upset with myself that I stayed and gave money to her business. Which will not happen going forward. I am a Harlem native and will tell anyone who will listen about their terrible service that day. Whatever she was going through wasn’t my problem and should not have been projected on me.

Until my visit to The Edge, I've never had a Jamaican/Caribbean meal that wow'd me, but The Edge was absolutely a rare dining treat! The cod fritters were crispy on the outside and hot, hearty & savory on the inside. Perfection! The jerk wings were fall-off-the-bone tender and spiced with a kick but packed full of flavor, not just heat. Finally, the oxtail with coconut rice was simply stellar! Deep in flavor and full of umami, it was one of the best dishes I've had anywhere and if available when you go YOU MUST ORDER.  As a side note, my friend ordered the fish of the day, which came out later than everyone else's food, but he was promptly informed the reason was because it had been overcooked and was being done all over again, which for anyone who hates dry, chewy fish really appreciates.  I was super impressed and have a whole new appreciation for Caribbean food thanks to The Edge ❤️ I'm already trying to plan my next trip back!

It tasted great though and I didn't feel heavy at all after eating a very generous large portion. We shared a half-carafe of the ginger margarita which was amazing. Would (will) definitely come back -- perhaps for brunch!

I read about The Edge in Thrillist’s “The Best Brunch Spots in 34 NYC Neighborhoods” list and took a guest from out of town. Overall would recommend!  FOOD: Great - Jerk chicken and waffles (pictured) was a good portion size for the price ($16). The chicken and waffles were a tad drier than expected, but the seasoning was flavorful and a bit hot. Not as spicy as I’d had, but still delicious! - Coconut milk coffee was strong and creamy! Definitely would recommend!  AMBIANCE: Great - Very lively! Sound carries, so you’ll have to yell a bit over the crowd at times - Tables are a bit close together, but you can’t blame them when it’s such a popular location!  SERVICE: Okay - It may have been a one-off experience, but our group waited alongside 3 other groups for at least 10 minutes before someone came to take our names down and give us an estimated wait time — long enough for me to call other restaurants and check their wait time. They also didn’t know who had come first, so there was a bit of an awkward shuffling around to honor those who were waiting longer. One couple that had been waiting before us left before the waitress even came. - After we were seated, service was just fine! Friendly and attentive staff overall!
